idth='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}, {"title": "Single entry point", "parent": "F", "actions": [{"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/data-2.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}, {"title": "MuralTagLab", "parent": "F", "actions": [{"show-side-text": "A segmentation tool specific for mural paintings<br> <video controls width='400' class='rounded'><source src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/muraltaglab.mp4' type='video/mp4' /></video>"}, {"enable-pois": []}]}, {"title": "Annotations", "parent": "F", "actions": [{"show-side-text": "Images can be annotated directly from FileMaker database <br> <video controls width='400' class='rounded'><source src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/Annotations.mp4' type='video/mp4' /></video>"}, {"enable-pois": []}]}, {"title": "OpenSeaDragon", "parent": "F", "actions": [{"show-side-text": "Easy image exploration through OpenSeaDragon <br> <video controls width='400' class='rounded'><source src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/osd.mp4' type='video/mp4' /></video>"}, {"enable-pois": []}]}, {"title": "Stories", "parent": "F", "actions": [{"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/story-1.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}, {"title": "Stories", "parent": "F", "actions": [{"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/story-2.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}, {"title": "Stories", "parent": "F", "actions": [{"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/story-3.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}, {"title": "Stories", "parent": "F", "actions": [{"goto": "cam-central-apse.txt"}, {"show-side-text": "Lighting simulation <br> <video controls width='400' class='rounded'><source src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/Candle-side-to-side.mp4' type='video/mp4' /></video>"}, {"enable-pois": []}]}]}, {"title": "G. Visualization", "parades": [{"title": "Visualization tools", "parent": "G", "actions": [{"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/vis-1.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}, {"title": "Point-based model", "parent": "G", "actions": [{"show-side-text": "Point-based model web-based exploration (Pau Nu\u00f1ez) <br> <video controls width='400' class='rounded'><source src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/pau.mp4' type='video/mp4' /></video>"}, {"enable-pois": []}]}, {"title": "VR tools", "parent": "G", "actions": [{"show-side-text": "VR tools (ThreeJS). <br> <video controls width='400' class='rounded'><source src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/Video-Arnau.mp4' type='video/mp4' /></video> <h4> A. Farras, M. Comino, C. Andujar</h4>"}, {"enable-pois": []}]}, {"title": "Navigation modes", "parent": "G", "actions": [{"show-side-text": "Navigation modes <br> <video controls width='400' class='rounded'><source src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/navigation.mp4' type='video/mp4' /></video>"}, {"enable-pois": []}]}]}, {"title": "H. Conclusions and future work", "parades": [{"title": "Conclusions", "parent": "H", "actions": [{"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/conclu.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}, {"title": "Pending", "parent": "H", "actions": [{"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/futur-1.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}, {"title": "Future work", "parent": "H", "actions": [{"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/futur-2.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}, {"title": "Acknowledments", "parent": "H", "actions": [{"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/ack.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}, {"title": "Final", "parent": "H", "actions": [{"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/final.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}]}, {"title": "I. Techniques and materials", "parades": []}, {"title": "\u25b9 I1. Techniques of Pedret's paintings", "parades": [{"title": "Techniques used", "parent": "I1", "actions": [{"goto": "cam-central-apse.txt"}, {"show-side-text": "Pedret's Romanesque paintings show a great technical mastery and a very good knowledge of the nature of the materials. The techniques used were the usual ones in Romanesque mural painting: <b>fresco</b> and <b>lime painting</b>.  <embed src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/mp3/fresco-and-lime.mp3' loop='true' autostart='true' height='0'>\n<br> <br> <img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/sample-virgin.jpg' width='400' class='rounded'> </img> "}, {"enable-pois": ["Christ", "Crownedlady", "Wise", "Foolish"]}, {"play-audio": "tecniques.mp3"}]}, {"title": "Fresco painting", "parent": "I1", "actions": [{"show-side-text": "The wall to be painted was levelled to apply, first, a mortar of lime and coarse sand (arriccio), and then another layer of thinner mortar (intonaco). This, while still damp, was painted with the pigments diluted with water. The carbonation of the lime amalgamates the pigments with the wall, without the need for a binder. This is the process known as <b>fresco painting.</b> <br> <br> <img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/fresco-painting.jpg' width='400' class='rounded'> </img>  <embed src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/mp3/fresco-painting.mp3' loop='true' autostart='true' height='0'> "}, {"enable-pois": []}]}, {"title": "Lime painting", "parent": "I1", "actions": [{"show-side-text": "As the mortar takes a short time to dry, fresco was only used for the first layers of paint and the backgrounds. For the final details, such as parts of the faces, folds of clothing, and decorative elements, the <b>lime painting</b> process was used. This consists of wetting the wall when it is dry and applying the pigments bound with lime water.  <br> <br> <img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/lime-painting.jpg' width='400' class='rounded'> </img>  <embed src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/mp3/lime-painting.mp3' loop='true' autostart='true' height='0'>"}, {"enable-pois": []}]}, {"title": "Pigments used", "parent": "I1", "actions": [{"show-side-text": "The pigments used were those characteristics of fresco painting. For the reds and yellows, earths and oxides. For the whites, the same lime, and for the blacks, carbon black. It is worth noting the use of the blue pigment, aerinite, to make some mixtures of greens, a mineral of nearby origin that is frequently found in Romanesque Pyrenean paintings. <br> <br> <img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/pigments.jpg' width='400' class='rounded'> </img> \n<embed src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/mp3/pigments.mp3' loop='true' autostart='true' height='0'>"}, {"enable-pois": []}]}]}, {"title": "\u25b9 I2. How to paint a face", "parades": [{"title": "How to paint a face", "parent": "I2", "actions": [{"goto": "cam-faces.txt"}, {"show-side-text": "In the painting of a face is usually used what has been called the \u201ctriad of colours\u201d: a light-toned background, generally light ochre, a darker tone to mark the shadows and a lighter one for the highlights. These tones were schematically superimposed one on top of the other. This system is contained in the 13th century treatise on artistic technology \"Schedula diversarum artium\" by Teophilus Presbyter. \n<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/sample-virgin.jpg' width='400' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}, {"enable-pois": []}]}, {"title": "Intermediate tones", "parent": "I2", "actions": [{"goto": "cam-faces.txt"}, {"show-side-text": "See description."}, {"enable-pois": []}, {"show-html-modal": "The triad of colours is the base but depending on the painter's skills and the means available, the shades could be extended with intermediate tones, as can be seen in this sketch of one of the virgins, where up to five shades have been used, apart from white for the lights and the final black to outline the contours. \n<ol class=\"list-group list-group-numbered\">\n  <li class=\"list-group-item\">1. Very light pink ochre base colour, applied flat to the entire surface.\n</li>\n  <li class=\"list-group-item\">2. Tone of the same range but more intense to highlight the left contour, nose, eyebrows, chin and eye bag.\n</li>\n  <li class=\"list-group-item\">3. The same more intense tone to accentuate the profiles of these parts.\n</li>\n  <li class=\"list-group-item\">4. Pale pink for the reliefs.\n</li>\n  <li class=\"list-group-item\">5. Darker pink applied on top to highlight the cheekbones and lips.\n</li>\n\n</ol>\n<br><br>\n <div style='text-align: center;'>\n<img src='https://www.cs.upc.edu/~virtual/img/paint-a-face.jpg' width='900' class='rounded'> </img> </div>"}]}]}]}